Analysing processed camera trap images - Oct 2016 session

library( holmberg )
pkgLoad( quietly = TRUE )
pkgLoad( c( "data.table", "dplyr", "imager", "sp", "ggplot2", "ggmap", "RColorBrewer" ), quietly = TRUE )
knitr::opts_chunk$set( root.dir = whichComputer()$home.folder, collapse = FALSE, warning = FALSE )

Get a list of all .jpg files in the session, along with their directory structure.

session.sorted.folder <- "/media/pinp/Seagate Backup Plus Drive A/Eastern-Barred Bandicoots/CameraTrapDirectory/sorted/Session5-Oct2016_sorted"
all.photos.vector <- list.files( path = session.sorted.folder, 
                                 full.names = TRUE,
                                 recursive = TRUE )
all.photos <- data.table( link = all.photos.vector )
all.photos <- all.photos[ grepl( "*.jpg", link, ignore.case = TRUE ), ]
all.photos %>% head( 3 )

Now split those links into their constituent parts so that we can find which species was identifed in each image.

all.photos[ , link.list := strsplit( link, split = "/" ) 
            ][ , link.list.length := sapply( link.list, length )
                ]

Let’s have a look at the lengths of those file structures.

all.photos[ , .N, by = link.list.length ]
##    link.list.length     N
## 1:               10 22466
## 2:               11    16

Looking at the data, we can see that most of the records have file directory structures of length 9, so they’re probably the ones we need. Let’s have a look at those 16 records with link length 10.

all.photos[ link.list.length == 10, link ] %>%
    head( 3 )

It looks like these are all unidentified animals. There are only 16 of these, so we can have a look at them:

unident.animals <- all.photos[ link.list.length == 11, ]

Looking through all of those images, there are a few photos of a pig, and the rest are of birds, which aren’t particularly consequential for us here. We’ll discard all of thes images from our analysis.

all.photos <- all.photos[ link.list.length == 10L, ]

That leaves only links with length 10. So we’ll now look at which value contains the species info, which should be the second last (we take the last 2 using tail, then the first of those using “[”).

all.photos[ , species := lapply( link.list, tail, n = 2L ) %>% 
                sapply( "[", 1L ) ]
unique( all.photos[ , species ] )

So that’s definitely the right value for species. Looks like only a couple of minor overlaps (eg: “Chestnut Teal (Duck)” should probably be under “Duck - domestic species only”). Nothing consequential for EBB monitoring though, so we won’t worry about those for now.

We also need a few details from each file name: the site number, the date, and the time.

all.photos[ , filename := sapply( link.list, tail, n = 1L ) ]

all.photos[ , file.detail := strsplit( filename, "_" ) 
            ][ , site.loc := sapply( file.detail, "[", 1L )
               ][ , date := sapply( file.detail, "[", 2L )
                  ][ , time := sapply( file.detail, "[", 3L ) %>% 
                         substr( 0, 6 ) 
                     ]
# also make a POSIX timestamp
all.photos[ , timestamp := as.POSIXct( paste( date, time ), 
                                       format = "%Y-%m-%d %H%M%S" ) ]
head( all.photos[ , .( site.loc, timestamp ) ], 3 )
##           site.loc           timestamp
## 1: E354894N5737342 2016-09-10 10:09:04
## 2: E354894N5737342 2016-09-10 10:09:06
## 3: E354894N5737342 2016-09-10 10:09:06

That looks good. Now that we have the site location for every record, we can associate a spatial location to each one. First, we convert the Easting and Northing values to GPS coordinates

all.photos[ , site.loc.easting := site.loc %>% 
                strsplit( "E|N" ) %>% 
                sapply( "[", 2L ) %>% 
                as.integer() ] %>%
    .[ , site.loc.northing := site.loc %>% 
           strsplit( "E|N" ) %>% 
           sapply( "[", 3L ) %>% 
           as.integer() ]

# convert the northing and easting values to latitudes and longitudes
coords <- SpatialPoints( all.photos[ , .( site.loc.easting, site.loc.northing ) ], 
                         proj4string = CRS( "+init=epsg:28355" ) )
coords <- spTransform( coords, CRS("+proj=longlat") )
head( coords, 3 )
## SpatialPoints:
##      site.loc.easting site.loc.northing
## [1,]         145.3359         -38.50047
## [2,]         145.3359         -38.50047
## [3,]         145.3359         -38.50047
## Coordinate Reference System (CRS) arguments: +proj=longlat
## +ellps=WGS84

Now we can put those GPS coordinates back into the main data frame.

# bring those coordinates into the cam.locations table
coords %<>% data.frame()
all.photos[ , lat := coords$site.loc.northing
               ][ , lon := coords$site.loc.easting ]
all.photos[ , .( lon, lat ) ] %>% head( 3 )
##         lon       lat
## 1: 145.3359 -38.50047
## 2: 145.3359 -38.50047
## 3: 145.3359 -38.50047

So we’ve now got the location and timestamp for every photo, as well as what species was identified. Let’s visualise what we’ve got on a map, looking at ALL camera triggers first up:

mapdata <- all.photos[ , .( count.total = .N,
                            count.ebb = sum( grepl( "andicoot", species ) ),
                            ebb.perday = sum( grepl( "andicoot", species ) ) / 
                                ( as.Date( date ) %>% range() %>% diff.Date() %>% as.integer() ),
                            lat = head( lat, 1L ),
                            lon = head( lon, 1L ) ), 
                       by = .( lat, lon ) ]

c.i.map <- ggmap::get_map( location = c( lon = mean( mapdata$lon ), lat = mean( mapdata$lat ) ), 
                           zoom = 15 )
ggmap( c.i.map ) + 
    geom_point( data = mapdata, aes( x = lon, y = lat, size = count.total ), col = "blue" ) +
    ggtitle( "Oct 2016 session, all triggers, trigger counts." )

Above we see all the camera data plotted onto the map, with the count of triggers represented by the size of the dot. Loads of activity in the paddocks, as would be expected with so many farm animals in those areas.

Let’s do the same thing with just the EBB triggers.

ggmap( c.i.map ) + 
    geom_point( data = mapdata, aes( x = lon, y = lat, size = count.ebb ), col = "blue" ) +
    ggtitle( "Oct-2016 session, EBBs, trigger counts." )

So this is giving us a really basic look at the distribution of the bandicoot activity. Those few hot-spots actually line up pretty well with my experience on Churchill Island, so I think we’re looking pretty good at this point.

We can also represent this same data as a density plot, since everyone loves a nice density plot:

ggmap( c.i.map ) + 
    stat_density_2d( data = all.photos[ grepl( "andicoot", species ), ], 
                     mapping = aes( x = lon, y = lat, fill = ..level.. ), 
                     contour = TRUE, 
                     bins = 16, 
                     geom = 'polygon', 
                     alpha = 0.3 ) + 
    scale_fill_gradientn( colours = rev( RColorBrewer::brewer.pal( 7, "Spectral" ) ) )

It’d be nice to have a comparative analysis to compare detection rates between sessions though, so we’ll also have a look at this same data as points again, but this time we’ll adjust the size of each point based on average EBB triggers per day, rather than overall EBB trigger total:

ggmap( c.i.map ) + 
    geom_point( data = mapdata[ !is.na( ebb.perday ) & ebb.perday > 0, ], 
                mapping = aes( x = lon, y = lat, size = ebb.perday ), col = "blue" ) +
    ggtitle( "Session , EBBs, trigger counts." )

Since most of these cameras were active for approximately equal periods of time, the main noticeable change here is the scale. This will be helpful though, when analysing comparative detection rates over time.

We’ll save the main dataset at this point, since we can extract a lot of useful info from it.

setwd( session.sorted.folder )
setwd( ".." )
saveRDS( all.photos, "photoData_session-oct2016.rds" )
